TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bester, Helmut
T1  - Bargaining, Search Costs and Equilibrium Price Distributions
PY  - 1988
Y1  - 1988/04/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297577
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 55
IS  - 2
SP  - 201
EP  - 214
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper studies a bargaining model of equilibrium price distributions. Consumers choose a seller at random and face search costs to switching to another store. In the market equilibrium, the prices at all stores are determined simultaneously as the perfect equilibrium of a bargaining game. In this game, the buyer has the outside option to search for another seller. Differences between the sellers' types create price dispersions; typically the number of active sellers increases with higher search costs. The market equilibrium converges to the competitive equilibrium under perfect information when search costs become small.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297577
ER  - 



